this is my  first session
vim modes
insert mode(where you can just type like normal text editor.press i for insert mode)
command mode(where you give the commands to the editor to get the things done.press ESC for the command mode)
most of them below are in command mode
x-to delete the unwanted character
u-to undo the last the command and U to undo the whole line
CTRL-R to redo
A- to append text at the end
:wq-to save and exit
:q|-to thrash all changes
dw-move the cursor to the beginning of the word to delete that word
2w-to move the cursor two words forward
3e-to move the cursor to tbe end of the 3rd word forward
0-to move to the start of the line
d2w- which delete 2 word ...number can be change for deleting the number
dd- to delete the line and 2 dd.number can be changed for deleting the numbers of consecutive words
p-puts the previously deleted text after the curso
r-to replace the letter 
ce- delete the word and places you in insert mode
G-to move you to the bottom of tghe file
gg-to move u start of the file
%-to find the matching
:s/old/new/g-tom substitute new for old where g is globally
?-forward search
/-backward search n to end the next occurence and N to search in opposite direction
:|- to run the shell command
:w-test save the file
v-start visual mode for selecting the line and you can perform operations on that like d delete
:r-file name will insert the content into the current file 
R- to replace more than one character
y-operator to copy text using v visual mode and p to paste it
yw-copy yanks one word
O-opens the line below the cursor and start insert mode
a-inserts texts after the cursor
A-inserts the texts after the end of the line
e-commands moves to the end of the word
y-operat yanks texts p puts it
R-enters replace mode until<ESC> is pressed
ctrl-w to jump from one window to another
the format for a change command is;operator[number]motion
-operator-is what to do,such as d for delete
-[number]-is an optional count to repeat the motion
-motion- moves over the text to operateon,such as w(word)
$(to the end of the line),etc
